<F P=100> INTER-AFRICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Frontline States Wrap Up Meeting in Harare </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Frontline States Wrap Up Meeting in Harare </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mandela Addresses Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> MB0406080794 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 0500 
GMT 4 June 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406080794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] South African President Nelson Mandela has pledged 
to lend a hand in regional peace-making and development in 
southern Africa. These two areas are expected to be the new 
focus of the group of Frontline States formed to combat 
apartheid. Speaking on the first day of the Frontline States' 
summit in Harare, President Mandela said South Africa will play 
a crucial role in resolving the problems facing southern Africa. 
In the same vein, he said, the Frontline states were still 
necessary to help establish democracy in South Africa. 
  At today's meeting the Frontline states are expected to form 
a new structure which will concentrate on other regional 
problems in conjunction with the Southern African Development 
Community. 
  When asked about the Rwanda situation, Mr. Mandela said 
South 
Africa had already agreed to provide a field hospital and was 
now considering leasing 50 armored personnel carriers to the UN 
for its risky operations. 
  [Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in English 0500 GMT 
on 4 June 94 adds the following: "President Nelson Mandela has 
returned from his first official visit to a foreign country. 
President Mandela, who attended a meeting of the Frontline 
States in Harare, lauded the Frontline States for their role in 
the dismantling of apartheid."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-23369 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr108bb_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTER-AFRICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Frontline States Wrap Up Meeting in Harare </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Frontline States Wrap Up Meeting in Harare </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Angolan President Addresses Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> MB0406085494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
0600 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alberto de Sousa in Harare] </F>
  [Text] The Frontline States met in Harare yesterday and 
noted that explosive situations still prevail in southern 
Africa. As a solution, the meeting called for continued 
consultations and joint efforts by the countries in the region. 
So, a decision has been made on the future role of the 
Frontline grouping. 
  President Jose Eduardo dos Santos briefed the Harare summit 
on Angola's political and military situation and, particularly, 
the Lusaka peace talks. The summit assessed UN efforts to end 
the Angolan dispute. The summit was pleased with the Angolan 
Government's decision to accept unconditionally the proposals 
made by the UN mediator regarding national reconciliation. The 
summit urged the National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola to adhere to the Bicesse Accord and abide by all UN 
Security Council resolutions. The summit urged the 
international community to increase relief assistance to the 
Angolan people. 
  The Frontline heads of state have also assessed the 
situation 
in Mozambique and the tragic situation in Rwanda. In addition 
to Angola, special attention was also given to South Africa. 
The summit was pleased with the successful outcome of the 
multiracial South African elections, which culminated in the ANC 
victory. 

</TEXT>

