<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RGF Shells Airport; UN Halts Relief Flights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RGF Shells Airport; UN Halts Relief Flights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0506123794 Paris AFP in English 1014 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0506123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kigali, June 5 (AFP) -- The United Nations suspended 
relief flights to Rwanda after government forces shelled 
Kigali's rebel-held airport Sunday [5 June] while a plane 
carrying Italian Junior Foreign Minister Franco Rochetta was on 
the tarmac, officials said. 
  The flights were suspended "until further notice," the 
officials said. 
  A Canadian C-130 military transport plane that had just 
landed with Rochetta and three other Italian officials on board 
took off again before they could disembark after a shell slammed 
into the airport behind the control tower. 
  Seconds after the plane left the ground, a second shell hit 
the runway. Nobody was hurt and there was no damage to the 
plane. 
  "The shells were certainly fired by the RGF (Rwandan 
Government Forces)," UN military spokesman Major Jean-Guy Plante 
told reporters on the tarmac when the shells landed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

