<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Summons Factions To Discuss Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assembly Summons Factions To Discuss Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0406202694 London BBC World Service in English 1705 GMT 4 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0406202694 </F>
<F P=104>  London BBC World Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Focus on Africa" program] </F>
  [Text] Liberia's Transitional Assembly [TA] flexed its 
muscles this week, and called on the rival factions to come 
before it and explain why they were still fighting each other, 
and why the disarmament process was in disarray and at a virtual 
standstill. There have been continuing battles between rival 
wings of ULIMO [United Liberation Movement for Democracy in 
Liberia], with Alhaji Koromah's Mandingo forces driven out of 
their headquarters at Tubmaburg by Roosevelt Johnson's Krahn 
troops. Flare-ups have continued between Charles Taylor's NPFL 
[National Patriotic Front of Liberia] and the Armed Forces of 
Liberia, AFL, and the ECOMOG [Economic Community of West African 
States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group] and the UN are increasingly 
exasperated. Well, the factions did send representatives to the 
TA yesterday, and it seems some were eager to shift the blame. 
From Monrovia, Nii Nartey Allison telexed this report: 
  At the meeting were Alhaji Koromah, leader of ULIMO's 
Mandingo faction; Hezekiah Bowen, chief of the AFL; and John 
Richardson, who was representing Charles Taylor's NPFL. 
Richardson told the assembly that the reluctance to disarm is a 
result of the failure of the transition government to assert 
itself in Liberia. General Bowen of the AFL said his fighters 
were delaying disarmament due to advancement on their positions 
by the NPFL, especially in the Harbel area. He said the AFL is 
ready to disarm as soon as the NPFL withdraws to its original 
positions. Alhaji Koromah said the ongoing war between the 
Krahn and Mandingo factions of ULIMO was preventing his fighters 
from laying down their arms. 
  Meanwhile, for the first time since the ULIMO conflict broke 
out, the leader of the Krahn faction, Roosevelt Johnson, has 
travelled out of Monrovia to Tubmanburg. ULIMO's Krahn faction 
captured Tubmanburg from the Mandingo faction a few days ago. 
Johnson is expected to set up an administrative structure in 
Tubmanburg. UN sources here confirm that Johnson's motorcade 
drove into the city amidst cheers from his Krahn fighters. A 
local journalist who travelled with Johnson said bodies littered 
the outskirts of the city. He said the city center was 
completely deserted, and that homes of Alhaji Koromah and some 
of his key commanders had been blown up by rocket-propelled 
grenades. 

</TEXT>

