<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Vorgan Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Vorgan Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0506205994 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0506205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alves Antonio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Some reputable sources contacted by Angola Radio 
Nacional here in Lusaka, who asked to remain anonymous, feel 
that the latest offer made by the government, which has already 
been presented to the National Union for the Total Independence 
of Angola [UNITA], reflects -- as has always been expressed by 
Angolan authorities -- the personal commitment of engineer Jose 
Eduardo dos Santos, president of the Republic, to reconciliation 
and national unity. 
  These sources also say that the government offer should not 
in any way be viewed as a weakness. On the contrary, they add, 
it should be viewed by UNITA and its leader Jonas Savimbi, who 
have claimed to be champions of peace and democracy, as a 
realistic and beneficial stand for the nation. The figures 
contacted by Angola Radio Nacional have called on the 
international community to pressure UNITA to end the bloody war 
that will have unforeseen consequences for the country. 
  Meanwhile, it is already known that, within the framework of 
the national sensitization campaign and pacification of hearts, 
the Voice of Resistance of the Black Cockerel will continue to 
broadcast in short wave, as an exception, for about 260 days 
once a peace agreement is reached in Lusaka. After that date 
and in accordance with the legislation in force, the UNITA radio 
will become a depoliticized radio station, broadcasting in 
adequate frequencies to be accorded to it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

