<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Swearing In of Deputies Discussed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Swearing In of Deputies Discussed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0306204894 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0306204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] A step forward was made here in Lusaka today. After 
15 days of discussions, the negotiating teams from the 
government and the National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA] today reached an agreement on the future of the 
Voice of Resistance of the Black Cockerel [Vorgan]. Radio 
Vorgan will not close down but its officials will have to follow 
the legal procedures for its continued operation. There is a 
law in Angola and Vorgan will have to abide by it. 
  The negotiating teams have already begun discussions on the 
next issue -- the swearing in of UNITA deputies. The mediators 
have already presented to the negotiating teams from the 
government and UNITA the initial document on modalities for the 
swearing in of UNITA deputies. The government says it agrees 
with the document. UNITA has requested time to study it but it 
says it will give its reply tomorrow. 
  A meeting between the government and UNITA, to be attended 
by 
Alioune Blondin Beye, special representative of the UN secretary 
general in Angola, and observers, has been scheduled for 
tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

