<H3> <TI>   UNITA Seeks To Replace Deputies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Seeks To Replace Deputies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0406203094 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] After the conclusion of discussions on the Voice of 
Resistance of the Black Cockerel yesterday, negotiators from the 
government and the National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA] are now discussing the swearing in of UNITA 
deputies in Parliament. 
  It is known that UNITA deputies who are presently in 
Parliament face the risk of losing their seats to new elements 
trusted by that organization. This stand does not agree, 
however, with the law in force in the country. The mediators 
have presented a proposal which does not differ much from the 
government's views. It now remains to be seen what arguments 
the UNITA representatives will present on 6 June. 
  Angola Radio Nacional learned that mediator Alioune Blondin 
Beye has been holding contacts with UNITA men with a view to 
finding in advance an effective stance [words indistinct]. In 
brief, it was a day without substantial changes in the peace 
talks, despite appeals from the international community to speed 
up the process in order to end the war in the country and reduce 
the suffering of the people, particularly the less privileged. 

</TEXT>

