<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA, FLEC Positions Attacked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA, FLEC Positions Attacked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0406080494 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 0600 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Our Cabinda correspondent reports that UNITA's 
[National Union for the Total Independence of Angola] armed 
forces in that province will not tolerate provocations by the 
government army. The correspondent says since mid-May, 
government forces have been involved in an offensive against 
positions of UNITA and the Front for the Liberation of the 
Cabinda Enclave [FLEC] in the northern part of the territory. 
The offensive has already claimed many innocent lives. 
  In a counteroffensive launched on 1 June, the Armed Forces 
for the Liberation of Angola [FALA] overran a People's Armed 
Forces for the Liberation of Angola [FAPLA] convoy moving from 
(Nicuma) to Buco Zau. At the end a four-hour fierce clash, 
FAPLA troops fled, leaving seven dead behind. Large quantities 
of war materiel, including four RPG-7's and three PKM machine 
guns were captured. In a separate incident, FALA destroyed a 
FAPLA motorized column moving from (Choa) in support of 
government forces in northern Cabinda. Nine FAPLA soldiers were 
killed and six vehicles burned. The survivors fled in disarray. 
  Meanwhile, latest reports from the city of Bie [Cuito] say 
artillery fire was exchanged last night. Light weapons were 
heard near government positions this morning. 
  No changes had been reported yesterday. MPLA-PT [Popular 
Movement for the Liberation of Angola-Labor Party] fighter 
aircraft continued to bomb civilian targets, while FAPLA 
infantry units shelled wards controlled by UNITA in a failed 
attempt to break through UNITA defensive lines. Our 
correspondent reports that decomposed corpses of government 
soldiers are scattered on the roads of Bie. MPLA-PT troops are 
using UN relief food earmarked for civilians. 

</TEXT>

