<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chissano Agrees To Meet Soldiers' Demands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chissano Agrees To Meet Soldiers' Demands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0406131494 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
0600 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Joaquim Chissano has pledged to meet fully 
the demands made by the 16,000 soldiers the government 
demobilized in June 1993, eight months after the signing of the 
General Peace Accord. SAVANA reports the former soldiers feel 
they were treated differently from other troops demobilized from 
assembly areas. They are demanding the payment of 18 months of 
salaries [words indistinct], pension, and what they regard as 
perks given to other demobilized troops. SAVANA says Chissano 
made the pledge at a meeting held in Maputo on 13 May with a 
commission representing the 16,000 demobilized soldiers. 
  The demobilized soldiers say if their demands are not met 
they will destroy business centers owned by Mozambican 
officials, boycott the 25 June and 25 September celebrations, 
and prevent multiparty elections from being held in October. 

</TEXT>

