<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meyer: No Powers Assigned To Provinces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meyer: No Powers Assigned To Provinces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0406090994 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 0500 GMT 4 June 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0406090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government of national unity is facing its first 
major test in trying to get the intricate system of national, 
provincial, and local government, agreed to by multiparty 
negotiators, off the ground. 
  Constitutional Development Minister Roelf Meyer said at a 
news conference in Pretoria that no powers had yet been assigned 
to provinces. This had been underlined by President Nelson 
Mandela's issuing a Government Gazette that temporarily assigned 
all government functions to central government ministries. 
  Another obstacle was that elections for local governments 
would take place only in a year's time. 
  Mr. Meyer said that the process of assigning powers to the 
provinces would take place within a matter of days and that he 
would meet provincial executive committee members on Monday. He 
would meet provincial premiers on Thursday. However, he said 
the question of financial transfers to provincial government 
still had to be ironed out. 

</TEXT>

