<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Report Failure of Government Counterattacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Report Failure of Government Counterattacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0606181594 Paris AFP in English 1749 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0606181594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kabuga, Rwanda, June 6 (AFP) -- Rwandan rebels have 
repulsed a counter-attack by the government army near its 
stronghold south of Kigali, the commander of the Rwanda 
Patriotic Front (RPF) said here Monday [6 June]. 
  Speaking from this RPF bastion around 20 kilometres (12 
miles) east of Kigali, rebel commander General Paul Kagame said 
his forces had repelled "some counter attacks that I wouldn't 
call a counter-offensive" amid intense clashes in the Gitarama 
region. 
  He said rebel units were stationed three or four kilometres 
(about two miles) from Gitarama, a town around 50 kilometres (30 
miles) south of Kigali where the interim government has 
established its headquarters. 
  Earlier Monday Major Jean-Guy Plante, spokesman for the UN 
mission in Rwanda, said governement forces had launched a major 
counter-offensive around Gitarama and south toward the border 
with Burundi. 
  Kagame added that the RPF also held various sectors between 
Gitarama and the frontier. 

</TEXT>

