<H3> <TI>   Western `Troika' Delivers Message to Tshisekedi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Western `Troika' Delivers Message to Tshisekedi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0306211094 Paris AFP in French 1546 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0306211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kinshasa, 3 Jun (AFP) -- Representatives of France, 
Belgium, and the United States in Kinshasa delivered a common 
message today from their governments to Etienne Tshisekedi, the 
main opposition leader of the radical opposition in Zaire, it 
was learned from a reliable source today. The contents of the 
message was not revealed. The governments which make up this 
"troika" are from three countries that are said to be close to 
Zairian affairs. 
  The political situation is still confused in Zaire while 
people are awaiting the appointment of the new prime minister 
who will be in charge of managing the transition period to the 
Third Republic. 
  A special commission, set up by the High Council of the 
Republic- Transition Parliament [HCR-PT] to examine the various 
candidates submitted, was to submit its report today to the 
HCR-PT bureau. 
  The Zairian opposition, assembled within the Sacred Union of 
the Radical Opposition [USOR], is divided on this procedure and 
the conditions set up to designate the future prime minister. 
  USOR radicals believe that only Mr. Tshisekedi should be 
appointed prime minister because he was elected by the National 
Sovereign Conference in August 1992 and then dismissed by 
Marshal Mobutu. 
  An important USOR faction, led by the Union for the Republic 
and Democracy, said on its part that the post of prime minister 
has become "vacant" and presented three candidates for the post. 

</TEXT>

