<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   NPFL Says `Diabolical Plan' Uncovered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPFL Says `Diabolical Plan' Uncovered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0606170094 Gbarnga Radio ELRL in English 1400 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0606170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Gbarnga Radio ELRL </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The NPFL [National Patriotic Front of Liberia] has 
received information from high ECOMOG [Economic Community of 
West African States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group] sources in 
Monrovia of a diabolical plan to plant arms and ammunition in 
several locations in and around Monrovia, only to be discovered 
later by ECOMOG itself and subsequently falsely linked to the 
NPFL officials in Monrovia. According to the high-placed ECOMOG 
sources, the motive behind the secret agenda is to effect the 
arrest of several key NPFL officials in Monrovia, including Vice 
Chairman Isaac Musa, NPFL chief negotiator John T. Richardson, 
and others, falsely associating them with the hidden arms racket. 
  According to ECOMOG sources, these diabolical lies were 
brought to their attention by a certain official of the NPFL 
cabinet within the LNTG [Liberia National Transitional 
Government], who continues to demonstrate insincerity in 
disguise to undermine the NPFL. The NPFL says it has identified 
this minister in question and is questioning his motives for 
continuously promulgating lies and deception against the 
interests of the NPFL. 
  The leader of the NPFL, President Charles Gankay Taylor has 
strongly warned that if such a diabolical plan is carried out 
with the view of keeping Liberia continuously occupied by 
Nigeria, and its officials arrested in Monrovia, this will lead 
to the immediate resumption of war in Liberia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-23460 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr109_e_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taylor Expresses Disgust Over Nigerian Actions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taylor Expresses Disgust Over Nigerian Actions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0606171594 Gbarnga Radio ELRL in English 1400 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0606171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Gbarnga Radio ELRL </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The leadership of the NPFL [National Patriotic Front 
of Liberia] has expressed serious disgust over a publication by 
Nigeria related to the cost of their peacekeeping operation in 
Liberia. 
  Recently, a local daily reported that Nigeria has revealed 
spending some $4 billion [figure as received] on what they call 
peacekeeping activities in Liberia. President Taylor said he 
views the pronouncement seriously, noting that this may be one 
of the reasons why Nigeria does not want to leave Liberia. 
  The NPFL leader reminded Nigeria and the international 
community that Liberia is not for sale, and if Nigeria claims to 
have spent $4 billion here, and did not use the money wisely to 
bring about peace, Liberia should not be seen as a Nigerian 
savings bond for their continued perpetuation in this country. 
  President Taylor said Nigerian reference to spending $4 
billion here is sufficient cause to believe why the Nigerian 
ECOMOG [Economic Community of West African States Cease-Fire 
Monitoring Group] soldiers are behaving arrogantly and carrying 
acts of treachery in Liberia. Are the Nigerians saying they 
will not leave Liberia until we pay back the $4 billion -- 
president Taylor asked -- stressing that Liberia is not for sale. 
  The NPFL leader said the statement by the former Nigerian 
vice president, that Liberia has lost its sovereignty in the 
war, is manifesting itself by the attitude of the Nigerians, who 
have commercialized efforts to return peace to Liberia through 
arms sales, drug trafficking, and support for armed groups to 
delay the Liberian peace process. President Taylor said the 
NPFL, through its vision, with Almighty God, will continue to 
fight, watch, and die, if necessary, in the continued 
preservation of the sovereignty of Liberia. 

</TEXT>

