<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Famine Situation Worsening </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Famine Situation Worsening </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0606151294 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1200 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0606151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA] has intensified its shelling of Cuito over the 
past 24 hours. Cuito no longer receives humanitarian 
assistance, and the food situation has worsened. Our 
correspondent Abel Abraao has further details. 
  [Begin Abraao recording] Wounded and hungry people in Cuito 
have been begging for humanitarian assistance. The political 
and military situation has not experienced major changes here in 
Cuito over the past hours. UNITA rebels continue to shell the 
city, after experiencing heavy defeats in direct clashes with 
government forces. 
  Despite heavy defeats, Jonas Savimbi's men are still 
determined to overrun Cuito. Over the past 12 hours, more than 
2,000 shells of various calibers were fired on the city, 
interspersed with infantry attacks. 
  Meanwhile, more than 500,000 wounded and hungry people are 
begging for humanitarian assistance from international 
organizations. People are already dying of hunger in large 
numbers. International humanitarian organizations have not been 
flying to Cuito for the past 10 days because of military 
instability in this region. Since the war began on 26 May, more 
than 400 civilians have died, most of them old people, women, 
and children. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

