<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border PAC To Recruit Members in White Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Border PAC To Recruit Members in White Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0706055994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2143 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0706055994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] King William's Town June 6 SAPA -- The Border region 
of the Pan Africanist Congress [PAC] has decided to launch a 
recruitment drive in predominantly white areas and to 
discontinue the use of the slogan "One settler, one bullet". 
  A resolution to this effect was adopted at a regional 
meeting 
at King William's Town at the weekend. The meeting was attended 
by the PAC's sole representative in the Eastern Cape 
legislature, Mr T T Letlaka. 
  PAC regional secretary Mr Mvuyo Mhangwane said the 
organisation would work with other community organisations to 
eliminate no-go areas in the province and to strive to make it 
"peaceful enough" to attract investors. 
  Mr Mhangwane said the meeting also endorsed the integration 
of Azanian Peoples Liberation Army members into the South 
African National Defence Force. 
  Structures to prepare for the local government elections 
would be set up, he said. 

</TEXT>

