complaints made last week against a memorandum sent to the 
Supervision and Control Commission by Colonel Segala, chairman 
of the Cease-Fire Commission [CCF]. The memorandum concerns 
differences of figures for government military personnel to be 
confined in 29 areas recommended by the United Nations. The 
NOTICIAS newspaper quotes Lieutenant Colonel Osorio Mateus, 
assistant of the government's representative in the CCF, as 
saying that our complaints are still in force. He questioned if 
there wasn't another intention behind Aldo Ajello's statements 
on 3 June, that the government withdrew its complaints. 

